    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If the Chelsea Piers sports complex is really beginning to make a profit (news article, March 6), this may reflect that its renegotiated lease with New York State deferred a large portion of rent payments for three years. Payments in lieu of taxes do not begin for two decades.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If the Chelsea Piers sports complex is really beginning to make a profit (news article, March 6), this may reflect that its renegotiated lease with New York State deferred a large portion of rent payments for three years. Payments in lieu of taxes do not begin for two decades.</p>
        <p>Why do New Yorkers, starved for recreational facilities, watch public land turned over to private developers who construct expensive, fee-charging recreational facilities?</p>
        <p>Chelsea Piers is the model for the new, misnamed Hudson River Park. Under this plan, too, state land will be leased to a development authority that will be required to develop revenue-producing uses.</p>
        <p>ALAN  HYDE  New York, March 8, 1998</p>
      </block>
